{"id":"1111.1619","submitter":"Yann Apertet","authors":"Y. Apertet, H. Ouerdane, C. Goupil, and Ph. Lecoeur","title":"Irreversibilities and efficiency at maximum power of heat engines:\n  illustrative case of a thermoelectric generator","comments":"5 pages, 3 figures, accepted for publication in Phys. Rev. E","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. E 85, 031116 (2012)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevE.85.031116","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.stat-mech physics.class-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Thermoelectric generators are particularly suitable to investigate the\nirreversible processes which govern the coupled transport of matter and heat in\nsolid-state systems. We study the efficiency at maximum power in the strong\ncoupling regime, where the thermal flux is proportionnal to the electrical\ncurrent inside the generator. We demonstrate that depending on the source of\nirreversibility we obtain either the Curzon-Ahlborn efficiency for external\ndissipation or a universal efficiency at maximum power for internal\ndissipation. A continuous change between these two extremes is evidenced.\nEffects of dissymetry of thermal contact conductance are also investigated.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 4 Nov 2011 18:22:08 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 1 Mar 2012 10:37:42 GMT"}],"update_date":"2012-03-16"}
